  <div id="work" class="container_12"> 
   <div class="grid_12"> 
    <h1> Projects </h1> 
   </div> 
   <div class="grid_8"> 
    <h3> <a href="http://visual.cs.ucl.ac.uk/pubs/tofconfidence/">Capturing Time-of-Flight Data with Confidence</a> </h3> 
   </div> 
   <div class="grid_8"> 
    <img src="imgs/tof_resized.png"> 
   </div> 
   <div class="grid_4 sidebar"> 
    <p> Time-of-Flight cameras such as the <a href="http://www.pmdtec.com/">PMD</a> CamCube provide depth readings at video framerates for much less than the cost of a Laser scanner. However the resulting readings contain noise from various sources, some of which (for example "flying pixels") are scene dependent and cannot be eliminated through calibration. </p> 
    <p> We train a <a href="http://www.stat.berkeley.edu/~breiman/RandomForests/">Random Forest</a> to compute a confidence in the range [0..1] for each measured 3D point. This confidence can be used to filter an individual scan, as weights for a method such as ICP, or as a prior for further processing. </p> 
    <p> This work was presented at <a href="http://cvpr2011.org/">CVPR 2011</a>, Colorado Springs. Full details and the most up to date draft of the paper can be found on the <a href="http://visual.cs.ucl.ac.uk/pubs/tofconfidence/">project page</a>. This is joint work with <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/J.Dobos/">Jozef Dobo≈°</a>, <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/L.Peel/">Leto Peel</a>, <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/T.Weyrich/">Tim Weyrich</a> and <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/G.Brostow/">Gabriel Brostow</a>. </p> 
   </div> 
  </div> 
